    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm working on this embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and i'm running into a serious issue. The system has a very limited heap, and over a period of about 4-6 hours of operation, we're seeing a gradual exhaustion of available RAM. It's not a sudden crash, just a slow crawl towards an OOM state.\n\nHere is a simplified version of the telemetry loop where we suspect the issue might be:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data(SensorData* data) {\n    if (data == nullptr) return;\n\n    // Allocate buffer for processing\n    uint8_t* buffer = new uint8_t[data->payload_size];\n    \n    if (!copy_to_buffer(buffer, data)) {\n        // Log error but might be skipping cleanup?\n        log_error(\"Buffer copy failed\");\n        return; \n    }\n\n    process_payload(buffer, data->payload_size);\n    \n    // Deallocate\n    delete[] buffer;\n}\n\nvoid telemetry_loop() {\n    while (system_running) {\n        SensorData* data = get_next_sensor_packet(); // Returns heap-allocated pointer\n        process_sensor_data(data);\n        // Is there a leak here?\n    }\n}\n```\n\nCan you give me a systematic approach to locating exactly where this memory is leaking? I can't easily run Valgrind on the actual target hardware due to resource constraints.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since Valgrind is unavailable, you need to implement proactive tracking within your embedded system. First, add meticulous logging to track every `new` and `delete[]` call, recording the allocation size and a unique transaction ID. Second, conceptually shift away from raw `new`/`delete` by adopting smart pointers or custom memory management wrappers that automatically track allocations. This approach will allow you to inspect the log data after runtime to pinpoint which allocation path is never balanced by a corresponding deallocation.",
