      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks, that makes sense. i'll look into the custom wrappers. i think i spotted a problem in the telemetry_loop though. looking at the code again, the `get_next_sensor_packet()` returns a heap-allocated pointer, but i don't see a `delete` for that pointer anywhere in the loop. \n\nso even if `process_sensor_data` is cleaning up its internal buffer, the `data` object itself is staying on the heap every single iteration. i'll add `delete data;` after the function call. \n\nbesides that specific pointer leak, are there other things i should look for? like, what if the leak isn't a missing delete, but something more subtle that's hard to find in the traces? how do i catch things that don't leave an obvious breadcrumb?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You are correct; the leak of the `SensorData` pointer in `telemetry_loop` is a definite and critical issue. Beyond simple missed deletes, look for issues involving cached or persistent data structures within your processing chain. A common subtle leak involves globally registered callbacks or static member variables that store references to dynamically allocated objects without ever clearing them. Furthermore, check for scenarios where error handling paths exit early without cleaning up resources that were allocated just prior to the error.",
      "source": "target",
